The Syrian refugees came in huge numbers to Jordan (occupying 10% of Jordan’s territory), forcing the country to allocate large facilities to separate housing, schooling, health and logistics infrastructure and systems. Though the influx occurred at a time of economic growth, the decrease in VISAs to outside world countries due to the economic stress backed up by the external energy politics, and pushed most of the Jordanian employers for two major decisions for the future of its business:
The shrinking of Jordan’s domestic consumer spending and high levels of unemployment forced most of the large regional companies to move Regional offices to more vibrant economies inside the region or abroad.
While many small and medium businesses (SMB) owners were pushed to international markets to expand their business, either by importing or exporting their products there.
The next several decades for Jordan are filled with varying degrees of uncertainty and uneasy optimism and hard practical choices. As in the decades before, Jordan’s future will depend on the future it chooses itself. Everything will depend on how the international community (especially the US, the UN and the EU) support Jordan in embracing its future (now coming fast).
